WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.600 --> 00:00:03.160
Good afternoon, everyone. Thank you all for being here.

2
00:00:03.340 --> 00:00:07.220
I'm excited to start the chromosomal

3
00:00:07.240 --> 00:00:09.980
instability educational session.

4
00:00:10.520 --> 00:00:14.200
As many of you know, chromosomal instability is a hallmark of human

5
00:00:14.320 --> 00:00:17.950
cancer, and really it is defined as

6
00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:21.660
ongoing chromosome segregation errors every time cells divide.

7
00:00:22.480 --> 00:00:26.000
Our normal cells have 46 chromosomes, obviously, and cell

8
00:00:26.040 --> 00:00:29.840
division has to be very faithful. So chromosomal instability is one of

9
00:00:29.900 --> 00:00:30.860
those features

10
00:00:31.780 --> 00:00:35.440
that clearly distinguishes cancer cells from normal

11
00:00:35.500 --> 00:00:39.440
cells. It's been known to be associated with poor prognosis and

12
00:00:39.500 --> 00:00:42.740
aggressive cancer behavior for a very long time.

13
00:00:42.800 --> 00:00:46.220
It's associated with metastasis, with therapeutic resistance,

14
00:00:48.040 --> 00:00:51.960
and with cancer relapse. And it's usually a feature of

15
00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:55.140
cancers that we think of in general as aggressive tumors.

16
00:00:55.840 --> 00:00:58.920
For example, triple-negative breast cancer, pancreatic cancer,

17
00:00:59.720 --> 00:01:02.160
brain tumors, ovarian cancer, et cetera.

18
00:01:03.260 --> 00:01:06.960
And while we've appreciated the fact that chromosomal

19
00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:10.900
instability is a driver of cancer progression, I think in the last

20
00:01:10.980 --> 00:01:14.580
10 years, there has been a lot of effort by multiple groups, including

21
00:01:14.860 --> 00:01:18.619
speakers from today, to try and translate

22
00:01:18.680 --> 00:01:22.640
therapeutic strategies that tackle chromosomal instability in the clinic.

23
00:01:23.180 --> 00:01:26.760
And so the session is really focused around two simple

24
00:01:26.800 --> 00:01:30.600
concepts. What are the cell-intrinsic mechanisms or

25
00:01:30.660 --> 00:01:34.560
approaches with which we can tackle chromosomal instability, and how our

26
00:01:34.620 --> 00:01:38.580
understanding of aneuploidy that arises from chromosomal instability

27
00:01:39.100 --> 00:01:40.500
creates these vulnerabilities?

28
00:01:41.440 --> 00:01:45.280
And also, what are the cancer cell extrinsic or immune

29
00:01:45.520 --> 00:01:49.250
mechanisms or approaches by which we can actually tackle chromosomal instability?

30
00:01:49.820 --> 00:01:53.640
So our first speaker is going to be focused more on the cell-intrinsic component.

31
00:01:54.180 --> 00:01:57.840
Our second speaker will be focused on the cell-extrinsic or immune component,

32
00:01:58.260 --> 00:02:01.180
and I'll be presenting at the end with two

33
00:02:01.720 --> 00:02:05.560
examples of how we can take that into the clinic, both cell-intrinsic example

34
00:02:05.660 --> 00:02:09.280
and extrinsic. So without further ado, I would love to

35
00:02:09.340 --> 00:02:12.900
introduce Professor Uri Ben-David from Tel Aviv University

36
00:02:12.960 --> 00:02:13.380
to

37
00:02:14.680 --> 00:02:18.660
talk to us about cell-intrinsic mechanisms of chromosomal instability.

38
00:02:21.340 --> 00:02:21.680
Thank you.

39
00:02:23.320 --> 00:02:27.260
Okay, so this being an educational session,

40
00:02:27.440 --> 00:02:31.400
I decided that I would not focus on one specific study, but I would rather give

41
00:02:31.420 --> 00:02:33.380
an overview of the concepts and

42
00:02:35.220 --> 00:02:38.760
try to systematically review how we can target cell-intrinsic vulnerability of

43
00:02:38.820 --> 00:02:42.420
unstable cancers and describe along the way some of our

44
00:02:42.680 --> 00:02:46.380
contributions to the field. These are our disclosures.

45
00:02:47.520 --> 00:02:51.420
So chromosomal instability drives cancer progression, and it does so in

46
00:02:51.480 --> 00:02:55.450
various ways. First of all, of course, the mere instability

47
00:02:55.620 --> 00:02:59.080
creates heterogeneity, and this heterogeneity

48
00:03:00.300 --> 00:03:02.220
basically makes for the

49
00:03:04.100 --> 00:03:06.820
substrate for evolution to work on.

50
00:03:07.840 --> 00:03:08.720
But on top of that,

51
00:03:09.620 --> 00:03:13.540
there are specific consequences of chromosomal instability that are

52
00:03:13.620 --> 00:03:16.079
important for tumor development and progression.

53
00:03:16.700 --> 00:03:18.740
So aneuploidy, which is the

54
00:03:19.960 --> 00:03:21.040
change in the

55
00:03:22.020 --> 00:03:25.900
copy number, number of entire chromosomes or chromosome arms being a very common

56
00:03:25.920 --> 00:03:29.700
and very important one and is largely the focus of the work in my lab.

57
00:03:30.300 --> 00:03:30.980
But we also have

58
00:03:32.380 --> 00:03:36.100
chromothripsis, ecDNA, whole genome doubling, and then there are

59
00:03:36.160 --> 00:03:36.820
epigenetic

60
00:03:37.740 --> 00:03:41.260
consequences associated with these changes, and this we will hear later.

61
00:03:41.320 --> 00:03:44.640
There are, of course, interactions with immune cells and so on.

62
00:03:45.960 --> 00:03:49.860
So the consequence of chromosomal instability are the chromosomal catastrophes

63
00:03:50.600 --> 00:03:51.640
which I've just

64
00:03:52.500 --> 00:03:54.100
described. And I think that

65
00:03:54.920 --> 00:03:58.560
in recent years we have had more and more evidence that actually

66
00:03:58.600 --> 00:04:00.500
link these specific events

67
00:04:01.340 --> 00:04:05.280
as bona fide drivers in specific context

68
00:04:05.340 --> 00:04:09.230
of tumor development. Now, when we think about targeting chromosomal

69
00:04:09.240 --> 00:04:11.460
instability, I think it's very important to

70
00:04:12.500 --> 00:04:15.000
disentangle the process from the outcome.

71
00:04:15.540 --> 00:04:17.680
So chromosomal instability is the process.

72
00:04:17.760 --> 00:04:21.320
It's the increased rate of chromosome segregation, whereas

73
00:04:21.360 --> 00:04:24.780
aneuploidy, as well as the other chromosomal catastrophes that I mentioned,

74
00:04:25.320 --> 00:04:27.640
is basically the outcome of that.

75
00:04:28.560 --> 00:04:30.400
And these specific

76
00:04:31.300 --> 00:04:34.740
events that arise and get selected for can also

77
00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:38.520
confer cellular stresses and may

78
00:04:38.960 --> 00:04:42.660
also open the door for some therapeutic opportunities.

79
00:04:43.220 --> 00:04:44.780
Now, when we think about targeting

80
00:04:45.800 --> 00:04:49.340
the process, I think we can use the analogy from the mutation world, okay?

81
00:04:49.780 --> 00:04:53.180
So if the specific

82
00:04:53.190 --> 00:04:56.900
chromosomal consequences, like specific aneuploidies, would be similar

83
00:04:56.980 --> 00:05:00.860
to a gene amplification, gene mutation that we

84
00:05:00.920 --> 00:05:03.600
may be able to target with targeted therapies.

85
00:05:03.740 --> 00:05:06.260
The process of chromosomal instability would be

86
00:05:07.220 --> 00:05:11.030
similar to the, or analogical to the mutagenic process.

87
00:05:11.390 --> 00:05:15.220
And so if you think about cancer therapeutics that take advantage, for example,

88
00:05:15.260 --> 00:05:19.180
of targeting DNA damage repair and so on, this would be equivalent

89
00:05:19.480 --> 00:05:23.320
to that. And I think it's important because often in the field, these terms tend to

90
00:05:23.400 --> 00:05:23.640
be

91
00:05:24.740 --> 00:05:26.120
mixed, and it's important to

92
00:05:27.860 --> 00:05:29.420
understand what we're really talking about.

93
00:05:30.960 --> 00:05:34.400
Now, it's also important to say that chromosomal instability and its consequences

94
00:05:34.420 --> 00:05:37.560
are strongly correlated, but they are not the exact same thing.

95
00:05:37.960 --> 00:05:41.780
Because you could think about scenarios where highly aneuploid

96
00:05:41.820 --> 00:05:45.440
cells are no longer chromosomally unstable or on the

97
00:05:45.500 --> 00:05:46.020
opposite,

98
00:05:46.860 --> 00:05:50.560
which is that chromosomal instability may be ongoing, but no

99
00:05:50.620 --> 00:05:52.500
specific karyotype would be

100
00:05:54.140 --> 00:05:57.980
selected for, or the cells may have reached

101
00:05:58.040 --> 00:06:01.930
an optimal karyotype for this specific tumor stage, at least, and these

102
00:06:01.980 --> 00:06:05.840
specific selection pressures, and then there would be no further karyotypic

103
00:06:05.880 --> 00:06:09.420
evolution. One example of that has recently been reported by the

104
00:06:09.520 --> 00:06:13.160
Satoriva and Graham labs, and this is from a commentary that we

105
00:06:13.400 --> 00:06:17.000
wrote on that paper, where they found that in

106
00:06:17.040 --> 00:06:20.940
colorectal cancer, at some point, even though at the single-cell level, there's

107
00:06:20.980 --> 00:06:24.440
still chromosomal instability, the karyotype remains

108
00:06:24.480 --> 00:06:27.640
largely unchanged due to very strong negative

109
00:06:27.660 --> 00:06:31.388
selection.So if we want to target the process,

110
00:06:31.588 --> 00:06:32.488
how can we do that?

111
00:06:33.688 --> 00:06:37.608
One option is to kill cancer cells by manipulating the CIN levels themselves.

112
00:06:38.088 --> 00:06:42.048
So the idea here is that we have a optimal range of

113
00:06:42.088 --> 00:06:45.948
chromosomal instability that is tolerated by the cells, but at the same

114
00:06:46.008 --> 00:06:48.588
time enables them to adapt and to evolve.

115
00:06:49.048 --> 00:06:51.728
Now, if we impair it, then we basically

116
00:06:52.688 --> 00:06:53.248
prohibit

117
00:06:54.088 --> 00:06:57.948
evolvability or adaptability. But if we also increase it too much

118
00:06:58.108 --> 00:07:01.868
beyond a tolerated threshold, this can also

119
00:07:01.888 --> 00:07:05.788
be used as therapeutics. And this is actually already going

120
00:07:05.868 --> 00:07:09.678
in with a well-known and a

121
00:07:09.678 --> 00:07:13.248
therapeutic. So for example, studies from Beth Weaver's lab have shown

122
00:07:13.728 --> 00:07:17.688
that the way that Taxol works, at least in breast cancer

123
00:07:17.748 --> 00:07:21.388
and in specific circumstances, is not by leading to

124
00:07:21.408 --> 00:07:24.728
mitotic arrests, but rather by exacerbating the chromosomal

125
00:07:24.768 --> 00:07:28.447
instability leading to more chromosomal

126
00:07:30.008 --> 00:07:32.688
aberrations that are no longer tolerated by the cells.

127
00:07:33.648 --> 00:07:37.628
Another way to target a chromosomally unstable cells is

128
00:07:37.668 --> 00:07:41.598
to exploit the stresses that are induced by chromosomal instability.

129
00:07:42.188 --> 00:07:45.108
So these stresses, this is from a review by Sam Becum.

130
00:07:46.588 --> 00:07:49.908
Some of them are directly related to the process, and some are already related to

131
00:07:49.968 --> 00:07:53.428
the consequence of this process. We can think about a

132
00:07:53.548 --> 00:07:57.208
phototoxic stress, replication stress, metabolic stresses.

133
00:07:57.888 --> 00:08:01.548
The idea here would be that these stresses in

134
00:08:01.558 --> 00:08:05.508
non-malignant cells lead to apoptosis or cell cycle arrest

135
00:08:05.548 --> 00:08:09.148
or senescence, and therefore chromosomal instability by

136
00:08:09.288 --> 00:08:12.488
large is not tolerated in normal cells.

137
00:08:12.808 --> 00:08:14.568
However, the cancer cells have

138
00:08:15.988 --> 00:08:19.928
developed adaptation mechanisms or coping mechanisms, and so if we

139
00:08:20.048 --> 00:08:23.148
target these coping mechanisms, we might be able to

140
00:08:24.588 --> 00:08:25.548
make CIN

141
00:08:27.148 --> 00:08:28.428
detrimental again.

142
00:08:29.428 --> 00:08:32.999
And the same types of stresses are really what we see with

143
00:08:32.999 --> 00:08:36.938
aneuploidy. So this is from a review that we wrote last year, and

144
00:08:37.509 --> 00:08:40.978
I'm going to tell you a few stories about how

145
00:08:43.369 --> 00:08:46.988
different types of stresses that are associated with aneuploidy can actually be

146
00:08:47.028 --> 00:08:49.368
exploited to kill these

147
00:08:49.788 --> 00:08:53.648
aneuploid cells simply by targeting the

148
00:08:54.328 --> 00:08:57.328
mechanisms that these cells deploy to cope with

149
00:08:58.188 --> 00:09:01.938
the aneuploid karyotypes. Now, in my lab, we apply experimental and

150
00:09:01.938 --> 00:09:04.968
computational approaches to look into chromosomal instability and its

151
00:09:04.978 --> 00:09:08.428
consequences. We take advantage of human primary tumor

152
00:09:08.528 --> 00:09:12.388
data and patient-derived models, as well as human cancer

153
00:09:12.468 --> 00:09:15.448
cell lines and systems of isogenic

154
00:09:16.148 --> 00:09:19.998
cells that we and many collaborators of ours develop, where

155
00:09:20.048 --> 00:09:23.668
we can look into the consequences of chromosomal instability or the

156
00:09:23.708 --> 00:09:27.588
consequences of aneuploidy in an otherwise a

157
00:09:27.668 --> 00:09:30.028
matched genetic background using

158
00:09:30.988 --> 00:09:32.448
different types of isogenic systems.

159
00:09:33.228 --> 00:09:33.408
Now,

160
00:09:34.688 --> 00:09:38.328
when we think about targeting these consequences of aneuploidy, we also need

161
00:09:38.368 --> 00:09:41.248
to distinguish two different types of

162
00:09:42.148 --> 00:09:45.998
approaches. So one is to look at highly aneuploid tumors or highly

163
00:09:46.068 --> 00:09:49.328
chromosomally unstable tumors and compare them to the diploid normal

164
00:09:49.368 --> 00:09:53.208
cells. In this approach, we're trying to find synthetic lethalities

165
00:09:53.248 --> 00:09:57.028
of the aneuploid state, regardless of the specific chromosome that is altered.

166
00:09:57.728 --> 00:10:01.088
On the other side of the spectrum, as we know, there are specific

167
00:10:01.268 --> 00:10:05.038
aneuploidies that are characteristic of specific cancer types

168
00:10:05.088 --> 00:10:09.008
and are hallmarks of these specific tumors.

169
00:10:09.028 --> 00:10:12.748
And if we identify vulnerabilities associated with these specific genetic

170
00:10:12.788 --> 00:10:16.548
alterations, then this could be also valuable for

171
00:10:16.608 --> 00:10:19.248
killing cells that harbor these genetic alterations.

172
00:10:19.688 --> 00:10:23.408
So I will start by telling you a little bit about synthetic lethalities with

173
00:10:23.468 --> 00:10:27.288
the aneuploid state, and I'll just mention kind of the

174
00:10:27.368 --> 00:10:30.128
bottom lines of a few stories that are mostly

175
00:10:31.008 --> 00:10:34.088
published related to these vulnerabilities.

176
00:10:34.128 --> 00:10:37.617
So if we start with the cell cycle and the mitotic regulation, which is also, I

177
00:10:37.628 --> 00:10:41.238
think, the case where really the aneuploidy and the CIN converge the

178
00:10:41.308 --> 00:10:45.087
most because this is really vulnerability of CIN and aneuploid cells.

179
00:10:45.188 --> 00:10:48.808
So a few years ago, we compared the genetic and

180
00:10:48.868 --> 00:10:52.508
pharmacological sensitivities of highly aneuploid CIN

181
00:10:52.528 --> 00:10:56.388
positive cell lines versus near diploid, relatively chromosomally

182
00:10:56.488 --> 00:11:00.328
stable cell lines. And to make a long story short, we identified the

183
00:11:00.348 --> 00:11:04.328
spindle chance assembly checkpoint and its regulator, KIF18A, as a

184
00:11:04.428 --> 00:11:05.968
unique vulnerability of

185
00:11:07.108 --> 00:11:08.828
chromosomally unstable aneuploid

186
00:11:10.608 --> 00:11:11.228
tumor cells.

187
00:11:12.248 --> 00:11:12.508
We

188
00:11:13.328 --> 00:11:17.168
uncovered a part of the mechanism that leads to this.

189
00:11:17.548 --> 00:11:20.168
There's still a lot that is currently ongoing.

190
00:11:21.298 --> 00:11:25.088
And several groups reached to the same conclusion at the same

191
00:11:25.208 --> 00:11:28.678
time. So Neil Ganem and Jason Stumpf's teams also identified

192
00:11:28.748 --> 00:11:32.588
KIF18A as a vulnerability of chromosomally

193
00:11:32.598 --> 00:11:33.768
unstable and

194
00:11:35.248 --> 00:11:39.088
cells with different types of catastrophic chromosomal

195
00:11:39.108 --> 00:11:41.568
alterations. And at the time, several

196
00:11:42.688 --> 00:11:45.348
companies, Amgen, Valastra, and Akcea Therapeutics,

197
00:11:46.168 --> 00:11:49.968
have been developing and are currently developing drugs to target

198
00:11:50.008 --> 00:11:50.568
KIF18A.

199
00:11:51.368 --> 00:11:54.168
These are in ongoing clinical trials.

200
00:11:54.368 --> 00:11:58.108
First results were published by Valastra last year and raised a lot of

201
00:11:58.148 --> 00:12:02.028
excitement in the field. I'm sure we will hear about it more in Sam's

202
00:12:02.068 --> 00:12:05.988
talk later today. But this is already a case where I think we can see the

203
00:12:06.068 --> 00:12:09.788
value and the therapeutic potential of this type of

204
00:12:09.808 --> 00:12:13.368
approach. I just want to mention that last year, in

205
00:12:13.388 --> 00:12:17.368
collaboration with Floys Fougere's team, we tried to go a bit deeper

206
00:12:17.448 --> 00:12:21.268
into the cell cycle mechanism that enables the sensitivity to spindle assembly

207
00:12:21.288 --> 00:12:24.948
checkpoint inhibitors. And we identified CDC20 as a key

208
00:12:24.988 --> 00:12:28.868
regulator of the sensitivity to the inhibition of

209
00:12:29.308 --> 00:12:32.604
the spindle assembly checkpointNow, more recently,

210
00:12:33.104 --> 00:12:33.364
we

211
00:12:34.344 --> 00:12:38.244
collaborated with Stefano Santaguida, and we wanted to take

212
00:12:38.284 --> 00:12:38.564
this

213
00:12:40.104 --> 00:12:43.704
one step further. So we generated isogenic,

214
00:12:44.464 --> 00:12:48.024
non-transformed Rp1 cells with varied

215
00:12:48.404 --> 00:12:52.124
levels of aneuploidy, and then we performed all the omics and all the functional

216
00:12:52.204 --> 00:12:55.844
screening that we could do. And this is a resource that is also available for the

217
00:12:55.884 --> 00:12:59.523
community. And that led us to two main discoveries.

218
00:12:59.844 --> 00:13:01.944
One is related to DNA damage and repair.

219
00:13:02.544 --> 00:13:03.604
So what we found was that

220
00:13:05.184 --> 00:13:08.204
once cells become aneuploid, they also

221
00:13:08.344 --> 00:13:12.174
exhibit a higher degree of basal DNA damage,

222
00:13:12.344 --> 00:13:16.224
and this is not surprising. The link between chromosomal instability and DNA damage

223
00:13:16.284 --> 00:13:18.224
is well established in the literature.

224
00:13:18.364 --> 00:13:21.464
But this also creates to a constant

225
00:13:22.024 --> 00:13:25.944
activation of the DNA damage response that renders these highly aneuploid cells

226
00:13:26.004 --> 00:13:28.444
more resistant to further DNA damage induction.

227
00:13:28.984 --> 00:13:32.724
However, at the same time, this leads to activation of a

228
00:13:33.404 --> 00:13:37.064
MAP kinase signaling, and in particular SRAF, which is important for

229
00:13:37.084 --> 00:13:40.844
the DNA damage response. And this has two potentially relevant

230
00:13:40.924 --> 00:13:44.844
clinical implications. One is that we show that you could use

231
00:13:44.964 --> 00:13:48.744
RAF, MEK, ERK inhibitors that are very important clinically

232
00:13:49.964 --> 00:13:52.404
to selectively kill the highly aneuploid cells.

233
00:13:52.854 --> 00:13:56.504
And the second implication is that by sub-lethal

234
00:13:56.524 --> 00:14:00.304
doses of this inhibition of RAF was

235
00:14:00.314 --> 00:14:04.164
sufficient to resensitize the highly aneuploid cells to DNA

236
00:14:04.184 --> 00:14:05.824
damage-inducing chemotherapies.

237
00:14:05.834 --> 00:14:09.124
And we discovered it with Rp1 cells, but then we showed that it's actually relevant

238
00:14:09.184 --> 00:14:10.264
also across different

239
00:14:11.344 --> 00:14:12.064
data sets of

240
00:14:13.504 --> 00:14:15.464
cancer cell lines and clinical

241
00:14:16.784 --> 00:14:19.924
data from patients. Now, the second

242
00:14:20.544 --> 00:14:24.504
discovery that we made using this new system has to do with dosage

243
00:14:24.544 --> 00:14:27.544
compensation. So the idea is quite simple.

244
00:14:27.604 --> 00:14:31.244
When cells have a aneuploidy and specific when they have extra

245
00:14:31.284 --> 00:14:34.864
chromosomes, then they need to compensate,

246
00:14:35.264 --> 00:14:35.844
especially

247
00:14:36.764 --> 00:14:40.603
for proteins that participate in complexes that are encoded from

248
00:14:40.644 --> 00:14:41.364
different chromosomes.

249
00:14:42.204 --> 00:14:45.504
And they do it both at the mRNA and at the protein level.

250
00:14:45.924 --> 00:14:49.104
So what we found was that at the mRNA level, when you have extra chromosomes, you

251
00:14:49.144 --> 00:14:52.084
have more transcription, but then there's also more RNA

252
00:14:52.824 --> 00:14:55.924
degradation that is mediated both by

253
00:14:57.184 --> 00:15:00.704
NMD and the microRNA pathways. However, there's

254
00:15:00.844 --> 00:15:02.964
still too much RNA, and therefore,

255
00:15:03.904 --> 00:15:07.664
there's also an attempt of the

256
00:15:07.684 --> 00:15:11.444
cell to down-regulate translation and to activate

257
00:15:11.704 --> 00:15:15.244
proteasome inhibition. Now, all of these create

258
00:15:15.544 --> 00:15:19.484
vulnerabilities in these cells, because if you interfere with RNA degradation or

259
00:15:19.524 --> 00:15:23.004
with protein degradation, then the highly aneuploid cells

260
00:15:23.044 --> 00:15:25.984
are particularly sensitive to that.

261
00:15:26.384 --> 00:15:30.324
And this is in particular important for proteasome inhibitors because proteasome

262
00:15:30.364 --> 00:15:32.844
inhibitors are used in the clinic for multiple myeloma.

263
00:15:33.244 --> 00:15:33.754
They failed

264
00:15:34.924 --> 00:15:38.064
in clinical trials for many solid tumors.

265
00:15:38.104 --> 00:15:38.854
When we took

266
00:15:39.664 --> 00:15:41.924
data from clinical trials,

267
00:15:42.984 --> 00:15:43.833
with proteasome

268
00:15:44.664 --> 00:15:48.264
inhibitors in multiple solid tumors, and we stratified the

269
00:15:48.304 --> 00:15:52.264
patients retroactively based on their degree of aneuploidy, we actually

270
00:15:52.304 --> 00:15:56.214
found that the highly aneuploid cells are more sensitive to these

271
00:15:57.504 --> 00:16:01.324
drugs. So now we hope to try to take it to more

272
00:16:01.344 --> 00:16:05.004
translational directions as well and see if it holds true in

273
00:16:05.064 --> 00:16:07.624
specific, interesting clinical contexts.

274
00:16:08.624 --> 00:16:12.604
Now, with that, I want to switch gear to discussing the synthetic lethalities

275
00:16:12.644 --> 00:16:14.424
of specific aneuploidies.

276
00:16:15.484 --> 00:16:19.444
And the first type of vulnerabilities I want to discuss

277
00:16:19.534 --> 00:16:22.364
is oncogene addiction and haploinsufficiency.

278
00:16:22.684 --> 00:16:26.504
Because now we get into the specific genes that reside on the

279
00:16:26.524 --> 00:16:30.384
altered chromosomes and not a general consequence of imbalance

280
00:16:30.464 --> 00:16:34.154
or of a high level of

281
00:16:34.244 --> 00:16:38.014
aneuploidy. So, also in this, we can think about

282
00:16:38.024 --> 00:16:41.944
synthetic lethalities here. We can think both about targeting the drivers and

283
00:16:41.984 --> 00:16:45.824
targeting the passengers. In this regard, the aneuploidy

284
00:16:45.844 --> 00:16:49.084
creates opportunities that don't really exist with specific

285
00:16:49.224 --> 00:16:53.164
oncogenes and tumor suppressor genes because we don't necessarily

286
00:16:53.184 --> 00:16:56.904
have to go after the target. There might be genes that reside

287
00:16:57.564 --> 00:17:01.064
next to it, for example, that are co-gained or co-lost

288
00:17:01.484 --> 00:17:04.504
and might be our target. So I want to tell you a few

289
00:17:05.644 --> 00:17:08.644
vignettes related to this direction.

290
00:17:08.684 --> 00:17:12.164
Let's start with the idea of targeting an oncogenic addiction.

291
00:17:13.065 --> 00:17:17.045
So chromosome arm 17p is one of the most common aneuploidies in

292
00:17:17.085 --> 00:17:20.884
general in cancer, but also in particular in breast cancer.

293
00:17:20.924 --> 00:17:23.085
This is true across molecular subtypes.

294
00:17:23.864 --> 00:17:24.045
And

295
00:17:25.065 --> 00:17:28.844
P53 resides on chromosome 17p. It's a major driver of its

296
00:17:28.884 --> 00:17:31.164
loss. We recently showed that even

297
00:17:32.524 --> 00:17:32.864
one

298
00:17:34.424 --> 00:17:38.064
monoallelic loss of P53 in the form of

299
00:17:38.544 --> 00:17:42.364
chromosome 17p monosomy is sufficient to

300
00:17:42.404 --> 00:17:46.284
down-regulate partly the P53 pathway.

301
00:17:46.384 --> 00:17:50.204
And in a study that we published

302
00:17:50.224 --> 00:17:53.764
last year that aimed to identify

303
00:17:53.784 --> 00:17:57.084
potential drivers of recurrent aneuploidies, not surprisingly,

304
00:17:57.184 --> 00:18:00.244
P53 came up as kind of the poster boy of this.

305
00:18:01.424 --> 00:18:05.104
It seems like a bona fide driver of loss of 17p across many

306
00:18:05.244 --> 00:18:05.924
cancer types.

307
00:18:06.744 --> 00:18:06.914
Now,

308
00:18:07.924 --> 00:18:10.584
in collaboration with the Sachi Fainaru lab, we

309
00:18:12.364 --> 00:18:16.324
found that aneuploidy-driven chromosome 17p

310
00:18:16.364 --> 00:18:16.664
loss

311
00:18:18.044 --> 00:18:21.984
can derive breast cancer brain metastasis specifically, and

312
00:18:22.004 --> 00:18:24.364
it does so by altering fatty acid synthesis.

313
00:18:24.584 --> 00:18:28.504
So the idea is that fatty acid synthesis is particularly required

314
00:18:28.584 --> 00:18:32.544
in the brain environment, and the inactivation of

315
00:18:32.564 --> 00:18:36.444
P53 upregulates SCD1, which enables

316
00:18:36.484 --> 00:18:39.724
the cells to synthesize their own monounsaturated fatty

317
00:18:39.744 --> 00:18:43.674
acids. And there's a lot of mechanism that

318
00:18:44.124 --> 00:18:48.074
we discovered in this paper. But for the sake of today's talk, I want to focus on

319
00:18:48.084 --> 00:18:51.908
the fact that this creates an oncogenic addictionBecause

320
00:18:51.918 --> 00:18:54.028
these P53 inactivated

321
00:18:54.848 --> 00:18:58.148
brain metastasizing cancer cells become

322
00:18:58.188 --> 00:19:01.068
dependent on the activation of SCD1.

323
00:19:01.498 --> 00:19:05.448
And there are several SCD1 inhibitors. Some of them are in clinical trials.

324
00:19:05.468 --> 00:19:09.438
And we showed in vitro, ex vivo, and in vivo that

325
00:19:09.468 --> 00:19:11.308
these P53 altered

326
00:19:12.128 --> 00:19:15.708
tumors and loss of 17p altered tumors are actually

327
00:19:15.848 --> 00:19:19.388
preferentially sensitive and very much sensitive

328
00:19:19.748 --> 00:19:23.568
to the inhibition of SCD1. And this is another thing that we're now

329
00:19:23.888 --> 00:19:27.788
trying to translate and see whether SCD1 inhibition could be

330
00:19:29.068 --> 00:19:32.268
a viable therapeutic against

331
00:19:33.548 --> 00:19:36.848
tumors with P53 inactivation, and in particular, in the context of brain

332
00:19:36.888 --> 00:19:37.568
metastasis.

333
00:19:38.388 --> 00:19:39.528
So this was

334
00:19:40.348 --> 00:19:44.068
published just two months ago with a very nice commentary written

335
00:19:44.128 --> 00:19:47.788
by Sam Baccom. And if anyone is interested, I

336
00:19:47.868 --> 00:19:49.648
encourage you to read the full story.

337
00:19:50.428 --> 00:19:54.348
Now, moving on to other types of these synthetic lethalities, I want to

338
00:19:54.388 --> 00:19:58.148
discuss hemizygous dependency. So here we're still

339
00:19:58.248 --> 00:20:01.108
staying with loss of chromosome 17p, but

340
00:20:01.448 --> 00:20:04.948
very close to chromosome 17p, there is the Aurora B

341
00:20:05.108 --> 00:20:08.528
kinase. And we found that Aurora B kinase

342
00:20:08.548 --> 00:20:11.928
expression, both at the mRNA and protein levels, is

343
00:20:11.968 --> 00:20:14.928
downregulated when this chromosome arm is lost.

344
00:20:14.988 --> 00:20:16.808
We see it in cell lines, we see it in tumors.

345
00:20:17.188 --> 00:20:20.308
In fact, it's the number one gene that is being

346
00:20:20.808 --> 00:20:24.508
preferentially downregulated when this chromosome arm is lost.

347
00:20:24.908 --> 00:20:27.948
And interestingly, unlike in many other oncogenic

348
00:20:28.628 --> 00:20:32.328
cases, in this case, when you have less Aurora kinase B expression,

349
00:20:32.708 --> 00:20:36.568
you become more sensitive, not more resistant, to the further

350
00:20:36.608 --> 00:20:40.428
inhibition of the kinase. And therefore, cells that have

351
00:20:40.488 --> 00:20:44.348
lost chromosome arm 17p are also more sensitive

352
00:20:44.408 --> 00:20:47.628
to alvespib than to other Aurora kinase B inhibitors.

353
00:20:48.308 --> 00:20:51.048
So again, I'm kind of just showing the final

354
00:20:53.568 --> 00:20:57.548
conclusions. The story is already on BioRxiv, currently in revision.

355
00:20:57.908 --> 00:20:58.888
But what we found is that

356
00:21:00.068 --> 00:21:03.908
Aurora kinase B can be a unique vulnerability of cancer with

357
00:21:03.948 --> 00:21:07.808
loss of 17p. We show now that it's not only in breast cancer, we

358
00:21:07.868 --> 00:21:09.828
see it actually across many tumor types.

359
00:21:10.278 --> 00:21:13.628
And what I think makes it particularly interesting is the fact that

360
00:21:13.728 --> 00:21:15.908
P53 is actually a

361
00:21:18.608 --> 00:21:22.348
regulator of Aurora kinase B. And when P53 is mutated,

362
00:21:22.658 --> 00:21:25.248
Aurora kinase B expression actually goes up.

363
00:21:25.708 --> 00:21:29.208
So P53 status has been suggested as a marker for

364
00:21:29.228 --> 00:21:31.928
resistance to Aurora kinase B inhibitors.

365
00:21:31.968 --> 00:21:35.508
What we discover is that it depends how P53 is altered.

366
00:21:35.588 --> 00:21:38.508
If it's altered by a mutation, then we see the same thing.

367
00:21:38.848 --> 00:21:41.928
But if it's altered by aneuploidy, we actually see the opposite.

368
00:21:42.098 --> 00:21:45.588
And we think that when you have both of them, because this is a very common

369
00:21:45.928 --> 00:21:49.608
way to biallelically inactivate P53, then you actually resensitize

370
00:21:49.868 --> 00:21:52.928
the P53 mutant cells to Aurora kinase B inhibition.

371
00:21:53.868 --> 00:21:57.648
So we think that, again, can also be important because, as you know,

372
00:21:57.728 --> 00:22:00.908
Aurora kinase B inhibitors have been debated and have

373
00:22:01.628 --> 00:22:02.368
largely failed

374
00:22:03.328 --> 00:22:07.268
in trials. And I think that, again, it goes down to the question of stratifying

375
00:22:07.308 --> 00:22:11.228
the patients, finding the right biomarkers, and the aneuploidy and chromosomal

376
00:22:11.248 --> 00:22:14.788
instability could be particularly important in this

377
00:22:14.828 --> 00:22:15.328
context.

378
00:22:16.748 --> 00:22:18.028
Now, in the last

379
00:22:18.868 --> 00:22:21.728
story I want to share with you, it has to do with

380
00:22:22.948 --> 00:22:26.598
passenger dependency. And here we're

381
00:22:26.648 --> 00:22:28.828
focusing on gains. So this is a study that

382
00:22:28.868 --> 00:22:32.548
was in collaboration with Flores Fougeray and Ramin

383
00:22:32.588 --> 00:22:33.068
Dekhoukhim,

384
00:22:34.948 --> 00:22:38.548
with Michael Schubert and Veronica Rendo, who led it when they were

385
00:22:38.588 --> 00:22:42.488
postdocs. And the idea there was

386
00:22:42.528 --> 00:22:46.188
that we wanted to look for genes that despite residing in

387
00:22:46.248 --> 00:22:49.528
commonly gained regions, so common aneuploidies that are

388
00:22:50.168 --> 00:22:53.728
gained, they are not overexpressed, suggesting that there might be

389
00:22:53.768 --> 00:22:57.628
selection against their overexpression and they might be toxic.

390
00:22:58.408 --> 00:23:01.328
And we combined this. Basically,

391
00:23:02.428 --> 00:23:06.288
we defined two layers here. One is this compensation, so

392
00:23:06.348 --> 00:23:09.267
there's DNA copy number gain, but there's no overexpression.

393
00:23:09.688 --> 00:23:11.447
And the other is that we took advantage of

394
00:23:13.447 --> 00:23:16.908
ORF screens, open reading frame screens, to look for genes that when you

395
00:23:17.248 --> 00:23:19.928
strongly overexpress them, they are indeed toxic for the cells.

396
00:23:20.288 --> 00:23:23.528
And we termed them ARGOS genes, amplification-related gain of

397
00:23:23.848 --> 00:23:27.668
sensitivity. And I just want to share one example

398
00:23:27.748 --> 00:23:29.468
for that. When you do this and you try to

399
00:23:30.828 --> 00:23:31.308
overlap

400
00:23:32.228 --> 00:23:36.048
these different analyses, we found that a gene called RBM14 that

401
00:23:36.108 --> 00:23:39.908
resides right next to cyclin D is

402
00:23:39.968 --> 00:23:40.828
actually

403
00:23:42.288 --> 00:23:45.748
one such gene. So you can see here that it is not

404
00:23:45.768 --> 00:23:49.588
overexpressed, despite the fact that it's commonly gained, and it's commonly gained

405
00:23:49.668 --> 00:23:53.628
because it resides next to a common oncogene.

406
00:23:54.568 --> 00:23:56.888
It's very toxic for cells when you overexpress it.

407
00:23:57.228 --> 00:24:01.148
We also validated it, and when we overexpressed it, we saw a lot of cell death.

408
00:24:01.168 --> 00:24:05.027
We partly characterized the mechanism that has to do with DNA

409
00:24:05.068 --> 00:24:07.948
damage repair, and particularly with non-homologous end joining.

410
00:24:08.348 --> 00:24:12.168
And we showed that this is actually also relevant in a clinical context, because

411
00:24:12.448 --> 00:24:12.628
if

412
00:24:14.508 --> 00:24:16.548
this gene is actually included in

413
00:24:17.628 --> 00:24:21.148
the amplified region and is overexpressed, then there's

414
00:24:21.228 --> 00:24:25.008
indeed a worse prognosis versus

415
00:24:25.048 --> 00:24:28.578
the other option, which is that only CCND1 will be amplified

416
00:24:28.988 --> 00:24:32.288
and RBM14 would not be.Okay.

417
00:24:32.728 --> 00:24:36.468
Lastly, I just want to say that I focused on aneuploidy, but in the

418
00:24:36.528 --> 00:24:40.348
lab, we also look at other consequences of chromosomal instability like whole

419
00:24:40.388 --> 00:24:43.928
genome doubling, chromothripsis, and many other labs

420
00:24:43.968 --> 00:24:47.708
also do it. So this is from a recent study by Paul

421
00:24:47.748 --> 00:24:48.428
Michel and Howard

422
00:24:49.508 --> 00:24:51.128
Chang that

423
00:24:52.348 --> 00:24:56.008
just got published. And found that in ecDNA,

424
00:24:56.388 --> 00:24:58.388
PVT1 is often

425
00:24:59.968 --> 00:25:03.728
fused to a strong oncogene, cMYC, as well as

426
00:25:03.828 --> 00:25:07.548
other oncogenes. And this can actually create different types of

427
00:25:07.568 --> 00:25:09.988
therapeutic vulnerabilities. So just two days ago,

428
00:25:11.608 --> 00:25:15.548
there was a commentary piece that we wrote that was published, and we think

429
00:25:15.588 --> 00:25:19.548
that you can think, for example, fusion junction neoantigens or different

430
00:25:20.608 --> 00:25:24.488
specific molecular mechanism that is described in this paper that might

431
00:25:24.588 --> 00:25:28.578
be relevant specifically for cells with extra chromosomal DNA.

432
00:25:29.208 --> 00:25:33.108
So to summarize, CIN can be targeted therapeutically in at least three

433
00:25:33.168 --> 00:25:36.948
ways. One is that we might be able to manipulate CIN levels below

434
00:25:36.987 --> 00:25:39.228
minimum or above maximum thresholds.

435
00:25:39.948 --> 00:25:43.528
Second way is to exacerbate cellular stresses that are induced by chromosomal

436
00:25:43.568 --> 00:25:47.188
instability and/or its consequences, or by

437
00:25:47.248 --> 00:25:51.108
inhibiting a stress coping mechanism.

438
00:25:51.408 --> 00:25:55.008
And a lot of the work that is currently going on in my lab deals with this.

439
00:25:55.508 --> 00:25:58.988
And third, we can target common CIN-induced genetic alterations, which are the

440
00:25:59.148 --> 00:26:02.488
specific aneuploidies. We generated the

441
00:26:02.708 --> 00:26:06.028
models and datasets to identify such synthetic lethalities.

442
00:26:06.348 --> 00:26:10.288
We have now aneuploidy scores for all the DepMap, about 2,000

443
00:26:10.328 --> 00:26:13.128
human cancer cell lines. We have novel isogenic models,

444
00:26:13.968 --> 00:26:17.938
and there's more to come soon. And we revealed novel dependencies, both of

445
00:26:17.948 --> 00:26:21.918
highly aneuploid cells and of specific aneuploidies, and

446
00:26:22.248 --> 00:26:26.058
I mentioned and discussed most of them

447
00:26:27.208 --> 00:26:31.128
in my talk. With that, I want to thank the people

448
00:26:31.148 --> 00:26:35.068
in my lab, especially those who led the study that I showed today,

449
00:26:35.508 --> 00:26:38.908
our multiple collaborators, the funding mechanism.

450
00:26:39.568 --> 00:26:43.408
And I just want to mention that in November in Berlin, there will be the

451
00:26:43.488 --> 00:26:47.148
first EACR meeting that focuses on chromosomal instability

452
00:26:47.548 --> 00:26:51.408
and its manifestations. And I want to welcome all of you who are interested in

453
00:26:51.448 --> 00:26:51.908
this field to

454
00:26:52.788 --> 00:26:56.108
register and to submit abstract. Registration is already open. Thank you.

455
00:27:04.808 --> 00:27:08.748
Great talk. Any questions? We have about four minutes for questions.

456
00:27:08.868 --> 00:27:09.948
Please go to the microphone.

457
00:27:13.508 --> 00:27:13.628
Yeah.

458
00:27:15.308 --> 00:27:15.948
Yeah, great talk.

459
00:27:16.968 --> 00:27:19.908
Question regarding your statement about 17p loss

460
00:27:20.888 --> 00:27:24.528
being dependent on SD1 amplification. Is there a gain?

461
00:27:25.268 --> 00:27:28.848
No. There's a regulation. P53

462
00:27:28.868 --> 00:27:32.798
transcriptionally regulates SCD1, and

463
00:27:32.868 --> 00:27:36.728
also regulates a partner of SCD1 that

464
00:27:37.608 --> 00:27:40.868
in turn regulates SCD1. There's no genetic amplification of

465
00:27:40.988 --> 00:27:44.728
SCD1. It's just that the loss of P53 leads to

466
00:27:44.748 --> 00:27:48.388
hypertranscription and therefore hyperexpression of SCD1, which

467
00:27:48.688 --> 00:27:50.748
enables the cells to synthesize

468
00:27:52.908 --> 00:27:56.268
monounsaturated fatty acids. And this is exacerbated

469
00:27:56.288 --> 00:27:58.788
and particularly important in the brain microenvironment.

470
00:27:58.828 --> 00:28:02.808
We also show that this is because the astrocytes secrete the substrates for

471
00:28:02.828 --> 00:28:06.528
this enzymatic reaction. So the full mechanism is in the paper if you're

472
00:28:06.588 --> 00:28:07.108
interested in it.

473
00:28:07.628 --> 00:28:09.348
Great talk. Second question.

474
00:28:09.988 --> 00:28:12.287
Hi, Uri. Shai Israeli from Schneider Children.

475
00:28:13.548 --> 00:28:16.488
I didn't know about the association between RAS and aneuploidy.

476
00:28:17.068 --> 00:28:20.748
And it's interesting because in the hyperdiploid

477
00:28:20.868 --> 00:28:24.108
ALL, which is the most common acute lymphoblastic leukemia, the most common

478
00:28:25.128 --> 00:28:28.828
leukemia in children, RAS mutations are part of this

479
00:28:28.868 --> 00:28:32.608
leukemia. So why is RAS is activated in

480
00:28:32.628 --> 00:28:33.168
aneuploidy?

481
00:28:33.937 --> 00:28:34.168
So

482
00:28:35.148 --> 00:28:39.048
what we found was that it seems like SIRAF is the culprit, because SIRAF has

483
00:28:39.108 --> 00:28:40.988
been actually reported to be important

484
00:28:42.168 --> 00:28:45.948
in different contexts for the response to DNA damage and chronic

485
00:28:45.988 --> 00:28:49.508
DNA damage. We also validated it in our isogenic system that the

486
00:28:49.568 --> 00:28:51.448
aneuploid cells actually, they

487
00:28:52.368 --> 00:28:55.608
express SIRAF more and they depend on SIRAF more.

488
00:28:55.668 --> 00:28:59.368
But once SIRAF is activated, the entire cascade

489
00:28:59.428 --> 00:29:03.328
of kind of signaling, the RAF MEK ERK cascade, gets activated as

490
00:29:03.368 --> 00:29:03.528
well.

491
00:29:04.008 --> 00:29:06.948
It's interesting because pan-RAF inhibitors, that's new.

492
00:29:07.128 --> 00:29:10.868
Pan-RAF inhibitors are now developed for neuro-oncology, so

493
00:29:10.908 --> 00:29:11.368
maybe it's

494
00:29:12.568 --> 00:29:14.128
useful for generally for aneuploidy.

495
00:29:15.048 --> 00:29:18.828
Yeah. No, I agree. I think we have several ideas of how to try to look into

496
00:29:19.028 --> 00:29:21.008
translational implications of this finding. Yeah.

497
00:29:22.088 --> 00:29:23.508
Great. And one last question.

498
00:29:24.008 --> 00:29:27.728
Hi. Thank you for the talk. So would targeting chromosomal

