1541
01:29:22.804 --> 01:29:26.644
I have two questions. The first question, there are different types of chromosomal

1542
01:29:26.684 --> 01:29:27.864
instability mentioned.

1543
01:29:28.704 --> 01:29:30.784
What is the best way to capture all of them?

1544
01:29:30.884 --> 01:29:34.684
Like, if you want to go to clinic, how do you capture all of this in

1545
01:29:35.004 --> 01:29:35.484
one way?

1546
01:29:37.524 --> 01:29:41.024
We could spend an hour talking about that.

1547
01:29:41.344 --> 01:29:45.164
Chromosomal instability, as Uri and Ashley

1548
01:29:45.204 --> 01:29:48.464
mentioned, it's a process of ongoing missegregation of chromosomes.

1549
01:29:48.944 --> 01:29:52.744
So there's so many different ways to look at it, and it gives you different

1550
01:29:52.944 --> 01:29:54.864
facets of that, of flavors. So

1551
01:29:56.304 --> 01:29:57.644
doing bulk

1552
01:29:58.804 --> 01:30:02.724
DNA sequencing, for example, will give you kind of a bulk level of aneuploidy, but

1553
01:30:02.784 --> 01:30:04.104
it won't give you the heterogeneity.

1554
01:30:04.224 --> 01:30:07.744
Single-cell DNA sequencing will give you better insight into the heterogeneity.

1555
01:30:08.504 --> 01:30:08.524
I

1556
01:30:09.644 --> 01:30:13.384
tend to like, if you're asking me, maybe I'm a little bit old

1557
01:30:13.424 --> 01:30:17.204
school or low tech, but staining for micronuclei is

1558
01:30:17.264 --> 01:30:20.684
actually a very good approach. Because what happens is

1559
01:30:20.764 --> 01:30:23.424
micronuclei-Don't live forever.

1560
01:30:24.144 --> 01:30:27.924
Cells make micronuclei when they divide, and these micronuclei can get

1561
01:30:28.024 --> 01:30:31.414
reintegrated the next mitosis, or they can kind of get degraded over

1562
01:30:31.504 --> 01:30:34.554
time. So when you take a tumor and snapshot,

1563
01:30:34.944 --> 01:30:38.374
basically put it in FFPE or whatever, and look at

1564
01:30:38.384 --> 01:30:42.204
micronuclei, it's giving you a snapshot of what happened in the

1565
01:30:42.264 --> 01:30:46.204
prior one to two cell divisions. And looking at the ratio of

1566
01:30:46.224 --> 01:30:49.004
micronuclei to primary nuclei probably gives you a good sense.

1567
01:30:49.044 --> 01:30:52.744
And this is agnostic to whether it's a chromosome arm or a whole

1568
01:30:52.784 --> 01:30:54.624
chromosome. You'll see it in HRD tumors.

1569
01:30:54.683 --> 01:30:57.124
You'll see it in homologous recombination proficient tumors.

1570
01:30:57.144 --> 01:30:58.664
So it's a good kind of broad capture.

1571
01:30:58.724 --> 01:31:01.664
The other option is to looking at mitotic figures in H&amp;E, but that's more

1572
01:31:01.704 --> 01:31:02.264
laborious.

1573
01:31:03.164 --> 01:31:03.264
Yeah.

1574
01:31:03.684 --> 01:31:05.114
My second question is,

1575
01:31:06.044 --> 01:31:09.584
for the cGAS-STING, this replication stress inhibitors like

1576
01:31:09.624 --> 01:31:11.504
PARP or like KYF18,

1577
01:31:12.364 --> 01:31:16.324
there are publications coming out showing that they activate the cGAS-STING

1578
01:31:16.404 --> 01:31:19.384
or that pathway, and that's how that mode of action is.

1579
01:31:20.344 --> 01:31:24.064
But here now I'm hearing that this is causing the opposite

1580
01:31:24.364 --> 01:31:28.204
of that. So is it like you need a certain level of DNA

1581
01:31:28.284 --> 01:31:32.144
damage or certain thing that now it gets reactivated, now

1582
01:31:32.184 --> 01:31:35.004
the type 1 interferon gamma is going up?

1583
01:31:36.364 --> 01:31:39.804
Yeah. I think that DNA damage can activate

1584
01:31:39.844 --> 01:31:41.254
cGAS-STING. There's no question, right?

1585
01:31:41.464 --> 01:31:44.794
The question is, is it acute strong DNA damage or is it kind of

1586
01:31:45.604 --> 01:31:49.424
smoldering, right? I don't think there's a

1587
01:31:49.464 --> 01:31:53.104
fundamental difference between our very simple experiments of giving the tumors

1588
01:31:53.164 --> 01:31:54.874
cGAMP on day one, day two, day three.

1589
01:31:54.874 --> 01:31:57.824
It's just that's kind of like DNA damage can phenocopy that,

1590
01:31:58.944 --> 01:32:00.524
but it has important implications.

1591
01:32:00.984 --> 01:32:03.144
So for example, I'm a radiation oncologist.

1592
01:32:03.524 --> 01:32:07.154
If we give a small dose of radiation to a patient every single day,

1593
01:32:07.844 --> 01:32:11.144
maybe we're sensitizing the pathway or desensitizing the STING

1594
01:32:11.164 --> 01:32:14.814
pathway, and maybe hypofractionation can be a way to

1595
01:32:15.164 --> 01:32:18.124
very strongly activate the STING pathway in tumors.

1596
01:32:18.574 --> 01:32:21.984
Again, I'm not arguing that this is the only mechanism, but when it comes to the

1597
01:32:22.044 --> 01:32:23.964
pathway, this is an important component.

1598
01:32:24.944 --> 01:32:28.804
There's been a lot of

1599
01:32:28.864 --> 01:32:32.223
work on PARP inhibitors and STING activation.

1600
01:32:32.744 --> 01:32:32.824
I

1601
01:32:34.364 --> 01:32:36.224
would like to see that in the clinic at some point.

1602
01:32:36.304 --> 01:32:40.064
But I think if we don't deal with acute activation, we may not harness

1603
01:32:40.104 --> 01:32:41.824
the effect that we're hoping for.

1604
01:32:42.594 --> 01:32:42.924
Thank you.

1605
01:32:43.144 --> 01:32:46.124
You're welcome. Okay, great. Just sorry.

